MNUMBER 133
NAME guard
ADJECTIVE 150
;
;choose one -- delete semicolon before choice, delete other two.
; HUMAN
; AVINE
; ANIMAL
;
; choose as many as are applicable, delete others
;
PART 00
; head
PART 01
;- body
PART 02
;- back
PART 03
;- right arm
PART 06
;- left arm
PART 07
;- right leg
PART 08
;- left leg
PART 09
;- right hand
PART 14
;- left hand
PART 15
;- right wing
PART 16
;- left wing
PART 17
;- tail
PART 18
 ;
;
*DESCRIPTION_START
You see an armed guard.
*DESCRIPTION_END
;
BODY 1250
;
;Defines the number of body points that are factored into the exp value of the monster.
;
EXTRABODY 600
;
;     Defines an added amount of body point between 50-100% of the actual number that is NOT
;    factored into the exp value of the monster.
;
ATTACK1 1100
;
;    Defines the monsters attack modifier of the creatures primary attack.
;
;
;
DEFENSE 900
;
;    Defines the monsters defend modifier.
;
STRATEGY 550
;enter a number in one of the following ranges
; 0011-100
;Non-hostile, flee when attacked. (note: if 1-25, the creature will also cry for help and alert legal authorities)
;
;101-200  Non-hostile, defend themselves when attacked. 101-125 will
;        cry for help and alert legal authorities.
;
;201-300  Animals that always flee even if not attacked but defend
;         themselves if attacked.
;
;301-400  Hostile, flee when wounded.  (group A)
;401-500  Hostile, flee when wounded.  (group B)
;501-600  Hostile, fight to the death. (group A)
;601-700  Hostile, fight to the death. (group B)
;
;There is no destinction between group A and B at this time.
;The intention  of the difference in the future will be that
;Group A and group B will be mutually hostile.

TREASURE 50

;     Defines the treasure level for the creature. If this is zero, the creature has no treasure.

;IMMUNITY (immunity #) (immunity level)
;            1-9            0-4
;    This defines a monster has having immunity to certain forms of attack. Or in some cases extra
;     susceptability to certain forms of attack. Immunity level defines how susceptable or immune it
;     is to that form of attack in half-units. 2 is the default setting which means the creature is
;     affected 2/2 (in full). 1 would be half damage. 3 would be 1 and 1/2 damage and 4 would be
;     double damage. All immunities, unless noted otherwise, are set to the default 2 except for #8
;     which is set to 0.
;
;The available immunities are:
;
;0 - Ensnaring attacks, particularly large or supernatural creatures
;    would ignore this form of attack.
;
;1 - Crushing weapons.
;
;2 - Edged weapons.
;
;3 - Heat attacks.
;
;4 - Electrical attacks.
;
;5 - Cold attacks.
;
;6 - Nervous system attacks. Creature would be immune to spells like
;    charm, sleep, psionic blast, etc. due to the lack of a normal
;    nervous system.
;
;7 - Life affecting. creatures would be immune to body destruction,
;    poison, disease and body restoration due to a lack of an active
;    "life force" or  are to unlike normal
;    life.
;
;8 - Undead affecting. This is the only immunity that is default to 0
;    and it must be set to a special value. When set to 3 it defines a
;    creature as a lesser undead, and includes creatures up to and
;    including a lesser wight. Setting it to 2 defines it as a greater
;    undead such as a mummy, lesser vampire, etc. Setting it to 1
;    should be reserved for extremely powerful undead such as a lich,
;    a greater vampire, etc.
;
;9 - Susceptability to death criticals. If set to 0 the creature would
;    not receive a fancy death critical. This should be given to any
;    creature that lacks a normal humanoid or animal physiology.
;RACE #

;     Defines the creatures racial group. At the moment this is only used in conjunction with certain
;     VALue settings on weapons for weapons of slaying.
;
;The available races are as follows:
;
;21 - extraplanar, creatures that come from other planes.
;22 - Undead
;
;23 - Arachnid
;24 - Kvantar
;25 - Troll
;26 - Lycanthrope
;27 - Giant
;28 - Constructs (either magical or technological)
;29 - Goblin
;30 - Ogre
;31 - Dragon
;
WEAPON 23 -1 100

;
;     This defines the type of weapon the creature uses. Weapon# is the archetype # for the
;     weapon. Adjective defines a standard adjective for the weapon and the weighted probability
;     is the percent out of 100 that the creature attacks with this weapon.
;
WEAPONPLUS 15

;     Defines the creatures weapon as magical with # being the bonus of the weapon. For obvious
;     reasons you want to be carefull not to set this value
;
ARMOR 70

;          Defines the percentage value of damage reduction that the monster receives.
;
;MAGICWEAPON (1, 2 or 3)

;          If this is defined, then a magic weapon is needed to damage the creature. If
;          MAGICWEAPON 1, then any magic weapon will do. 2 requires a bonus of at least
;          +10. 3 requires a bonus of at least +21.
;
;    SKINADJ [#]

;          Defines the standard adjective number to attach to any items skinned
;
;         SKINITEM [item#] [probability] [coppervalue] [magic]
;
;              Item# defines the archetype number of a certain skin that is available on a givenr
;               monster. The"probability" is another weighted probability similar to that used for
;               distibuting weapon selection. "Coppervalue is the items average value in copper.
;               "Magic is a number thatwhich specifies the magic content of the item. If 0 which
;               most skins should be, the item is non-magical. Otherwise it is a spell
;               component.Some item archetypes you may use for creature skins are:
;
;          504 - beard
;          505 - claw
;          506 - scalp
;          507 - scale
;          508 - ear
;          509 - pelt
;          510 - tooth
;          512 - dust
;          513 - talon
;          514 - hide
;          515 - hair
;          516 - beak
;          517 - feathers
;          518 - paw
;          519 - horn
;          520 - eye
;          521 - tongue
;          522 - tail
;          523 - skin
;          524 - tusk
;          525 - finger
;          526 - toe
;          527 - leg
;          528 - fangs
;
DISCORPORATE
;
;               This indicates that if the monster is killed it will not leave a corpse behind.
;
;          ETERNAL
;
;               This indicates that the creature will not be unloaded by the system until it is
;               killed.
;
GENDER 0
;
;          0 - male,
;          1 - female
;          2 - neutral (defualt)
;
STEALABLE
;
;               This indicates the monster may be stolen from.
;
;POISON [% chance] [x]
;
;               If defined, this provides a percent chance that a level x poison is delivered to the
;               victim upon being struck.
;
;         DISEASE [% chance] [x]
;
;               This is basically the same as POISON.
;
;         FATIGUE [%chance] [x]
;
;               This is the equivalent of a life draining attack.
;
RESIST 325
;               This defines the creatures magic resistance.
;
SPEED 1
;
;               The default setting is 3. It defines how fast the creature attacks and moves. 1 is
;               fastest and 4 or more is for extremely slow creatures.
;
;HIDESKILL [X]
;
;               This defines a percentage chance that the creature will be able to hide. it is also
;;;               used to define the creatures skill at backstab. X is the base chance. Warning: do
;               not define X above 100.
;
;         GUARD [X]

;               defines what creature this monster will guard where X is the monster number that
;               is to be guarded.
;
;UNIQUE

;               Indicates that this creature is unique and has a personal rather than general name.
;               Use this definition BEFORE defining the creatures name.
;
;
;          Spell Casting
;
 MANA 700

;               Defines the number of mana points a monster has.
;
SPELLUSE 33
;
;               Defines the chance of the monster using its spells as opposed to its weapon or
;               special attack.
;
SPELLSKILL 120
;
;               Defines the base spellcraft skill the creature has.
;
CASTLEVEL 60
;
;               Defines the duration of a creatures spell.
;
NONDISRUPTABLE
;
;               This indicates that the creature's spell will not be disrupted by an attack.
;
;SILENCEIGNORE
;
;               This indicates that the Silence spell will not affect the creature's ability to cast a
;               spell.
;
SPELL 112
;
;               Grants the creature the given spell. NOTE: Not all spells will work but almost all
;               offensive and defensive spells will work.
;
;
;          Psionics
;
PSIRESIST 326

;               Defines the creature's psionic resistance. If you don't specify any, it will default
;               to the same as its normal magic resistance. (Note: This is a monsters resistance
;               to mental attacks, ie stuns).
;
PSI 750
;
;               The number of psi points the creature has.
;
;   DISCIPLINE [x]

;               Gives the creature the psionic discipline # you specify.
;
;         PSIUSE [x]

;               Specifies a percentage (1-100) of the time that this creature will opt
;
;              PSISKILL [x]

;                    The total chance that the psionic creature has when invoking apsionic
;                    power. Powerful psionic creatures should have well overa 100 so as to
;                    defeat a player's natural resistance to psionics.
;
;PSILEVEL [x]
;
;                    The creature's effective skill level in the Mind over Matter skill. This is
;                    used for determining the effectiveness of Cryokinetics, Pyrokinetics,
;                    Electrify and Kinetic Thrust.
;
;

;               Besides giving a creature spells to cast, you may give it a "special attack form"
;               which is an attack that always works.
;
;              SPECUSE [%chance]
;
;                    Defines the percent chance that the creature will choose to use its special
;                    attack in preference to other attacks.
;
;              SPECUSES [x]
;
;                    Limits the creatures ability to use its special attack to x times.
;
;              SPECBASE [x]
;
;                    Sets the [minimum] damage that this attack will do.
;
;              SPECDMG [x]
;
;                    Sets the additional [random] damage range that this attack will do.
;
;              SPECDMGTYPE [Heat, cold, slash, electric]
;
;                    Sets the damage type for special attack forms.
;
;              TEXX [special attack text output..]
;
;                    This text assumes the following format. "%s blah blah blah %s." You must
;                    have the two %s strings in there. They have nothing to do with the echo
;                    command uses. They are replaced with the attacking creatures name and
;                    the victim creatures name respectively. do not include quotes in your
;                    definition.
;               Example: TEXX %s breathes a gout of flame at %s!
;
;               Redifining the Defualt text fields for monsters
;
;                    The text fields may be redefined by using the TEX? commands.
;               Example: TEXH A thief fails to sink into the shadows.
;                    Redefines the text for a certain creature that is shown when that creature
;                    fails its % chance to hide. The available redefinitions are as follows.
TEXD His body disappears in a flash of colored smoke.


